Our division of the plays into numbered Acts and Seenes dates only from the Renaissance editions, and though useful for , purposes of reference should not have any prominence assigned to it. In the ancient recensions the only division was that indicated by the scene- headings. These were written as a rule in two lines, the name of the speaker in the first and his ‘role' in the second, eg.

ERGASILVS PARASITVS.

In a very early archetype of the ‘Palatine' recension the first lines of these scene—headings had been lost, though they were in most cases supplied by conjecture in a later copy (see Introd. i. ξ 14). That is why our MSS. here offer only the title of the rffle, PARAsrrvs. Often however the scene-headings seem to have occupied one line, instead of two, and to have comprised only the proper names, not the rOles (eg. 111. ii. ⁴2, iii. 2, iv. 2, v.‘.2‚ IV. iv„ v. i.‚ iii„ iv.).

Ergasilus, the parasite ¹, comes on the stage, looking very lean and woe- begone (cf. vv, 91 sqq.‚ 133 sqq), and laments the absence of his young patron Philopolemus, with its attendant inconveniences for himself.

This opening scene curiously resembles that of the Menaechmi, whose prologue too, as already mentioned (p. 115), with its laboured explanation of a somewhat intricate plot, reminds us of the prologue to the Captivi. The parasite in the Menaechmi begins like Ergasilus, with an avowal of his nickname:

quentus nomen fecit Peniculo mihi, Ideo quia mensam, quando edo, detergeo,

and goes on to suggest that the most binding fetters for a prisoner in the ⁴ ergastulum' would be a good dinner:

Esca atque potione uinciri decet. Apud mensam plenam homini rostri deliges.
